Introduction

Decoding Tipping Patterns

Tipping is a complex social and economic behavior influenced by a variety of factors, including service quality, cultural norms, and customer demographics. While tipping is often seen as a simple gesture of appreciation, it reflects deeper patterns that can be analyzed and predicted using data-driven approaches. This project leverages theÂ TIPS dataset, which records tipping behavior in a restaurant setting, to explore the factors influencing tipping and build predictive models for tip amounts and percentages. By combining exploratory data analysis with machine learning techniques, we aim to uncover actionable insights that can benefit restaurant owners, service staff, and customers alike.

Our goal is to answer the following questions:

  1. Which factors have the strongest influence on tipping behavior?

    After feature selection,Â BillÂ andÂ PartySizeÂ demonstrated the strongest numerical correlations withÂ TipPercentageÂ andÂ TipCategory. However, the modelsâ limitations indicate that unobserved factors, like service quality and customer satisfaction, likely play a significant role.

  2. How accurately can we predict tip amounts and percentages? What machine learning models perform best in predicting tipping behavior, and how reliable are their predictions?

    With initial modeling, accuracy was poor. However, after applying correlation-based feature selection, the Ridge regression model significantly improved in predictingÂ TipPercentageÂ (RMSE: 1.76, R-squared: 0.876), and the KNN model substantially improved in predictingÂ TipCategoryÂ (Accuracy: 0.865).

    After feature selection, the Ridge regression model performed slightly better than the linear regression model for predictingÂ TipPercentage, and the KNN model performed well for predictingÂ TipCategory. While feature selection greatly improved reliability, further research with more data and models may be needed to achieve higher accuracy.

  3. What actionable insights can restaurants derive from this analysis?

    Restaurants should cautiously consider the relationships betweenÂ Bill,Â PartySize, andÂ TimeÂ with tipping patterns, but recognize the importance of unobserved factors. Focusing on enhancing service quality, gathering customer feedback, and exploring additional relevant variables could improve customer satisfaction and revenue.

By analyzing this dataset, we aim to uncover patterns and relationships that can help us better understand tipping behavior and provide actionable insights for the restaurant industry.

Understanding the data

Today we will be working with the TIPS data set which is in the regclass package. The data in the TIPS dataset is information recorded by one waiter about each tip he received over a period of a few months working in a restaurant.

Exercise 2: Visualizing Distributions

This exercise focuses on visualizing the distributions of both numerical and categorical variables within the TIPS dataset. We aim to identify any skewness, outliers, or unusual patterns that might influence our subsequent analysis and modeling.

library(ggplot2)

# Histogram for Bill
ggplot(TIPS, aes(x = Bill)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, fill = "blue", color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Bill Amounts", x = "Bill ($)", y = "Frequency")
# Histogram for Tip
ggplot(TIPS, aes(x = Tip)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, fill = "green", color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Tip Amounts", x = "Tip ($)", y = "Frequency")
# Histogram for TipPercentage
ggplot(TIPS, aes(x = TipPercentage)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, fill = "red", color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Tip Percentages", x = "Tip Percentage (%)", y = "Frequency")
# Bar plot for Gender
ggplot(TIPS, aes(x = Gender)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "purple") +
  labs(title = "Count of Tips by Gender", x = "Gender", y = "Count")
# Bar plot for Smoker
ggplot(TIPS, aes(x = Smoker)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "brown") +
  labs(title = "Count of Tips by Smoker Status", x = "Smoker", y = "Count")
# Bar plot for Weekday
ggplot(TIPS, aes(x = Weekday)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "orange") +
  labs(title = "Count of Tips by Day of the Week", x = "Day", y = "Count")
# Bar plot for Time
ggplot(TIPS, aes(x = Time)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "cyan") +
  labs(title = "Count of Tips by Time of Day", x = "Time", y = "Count")

Observations:

  • Bill: The distribution is right-skewed, with most bills ranging between 10 and 40.

  • Tip: The distribution is also right-skewed, with most tips ranging between 1 and 5.

  • TipPercentage: A few outliers exceed 30%, but most tips fall within 10% to 20%.

  • Gender: More tips are recorded from males than females.

  • Smoker: Non-smokers account for more tips than smokers.

  • Weekday: Most tips are recorded on weekends (Saturday and Sunday).

  • Time: More tips are recorded at night than during the day.

Exercise 4: Feature Engineering and Data Preparation

In this exercise, we will perform feature engineering to create derived features and prepare the data for predictive modeling. This includes encoding categorical variables, scaling and centering numerical features, and addressing any missing values.

# Feature Engineering
#interaction variable
TIPS <- TIPS |>
  mutate(PartyDay = PartySize * as.numeric(Weekday))

# Encode categorical variables
TIPS_encoded <- TIPS |>
  mutate(Gender = as.factor(Gender),
         Smoker = as.factor(Smoker),
         Weekday = as.factor(Weekday),
         Time = as.factor(Time)) |>
  mutate_if(is.factor, as.numeric)

# Scale and normalize numerical features
preprocess_obj <- preProcess(TIPS_encoded, method = c("center", "scale"))
TIPS_preprocessed <- predict(preprocess_obj, TIPS_encoded)

# Check for missing values
sum(is.na(TIPS_preprocessed))
[1] 0

Observations:

  • An interaction variable âPartyDayâ was created.

  • Categorical variables were numerically encoded.

  • Numerical features were scaled and centered.

  • There are no missing values in the preprocessed data.

Exercise 5: Identify Outliers and Data Splitting

This exercise aims to identify and visualize potential outliers in theÂ TipPercentageÂ variable and toÂ prepare the data for modeling by encoding categorical variables and splitting the dataset into training and testing sets.

# Identify outliers in TipPercentage
boxplot(TIPS$TipPercentage, main = "Boxplot of Tip Percentage", ylab = "Tip Percentage (%)")
# Encode categorical variables
TIPS_encoded <- TIPS |>
  mutate(Gender = as.numeric(Gender) - 1,  # Female = 0, Male = 1

# Split the data
library(tidymodels)
set.seed(427)
split <- initial_split(TIPS_encoded, prop = 0.7)
train_data <- training(split)
test_data <- testing(split)

Observations:

  • A boxplot ofÂ TipPercentageÂ is created to visually identify potential outliers.

  • The categorical variablesÂ Gender,Â Smoker, andÂ TimeÂ are numerically encoded.

  • The dataset is split into 70% training data and 30% testing data for model development and evaluation.

Exercise 6: Predictive Modeling

In this exercise, we will build predictive models to forecast tip amounts and percentages based on the features in the TIPS dataset. We will explore both regression and classification approaches, using linear regression and KNN. We will focus on the regression model first, and then move to the classification model.

library(parsnip)
library(yardstick)

# Linear Regression Model for TipPercentage 
lm_model <- linear_reg() |>
  set_engine("lm") |>
  set_mode("regression")

lm_fit <- lm_model |>
  fit(TipPercentage ~ Bill + PartySize + Gender + Smoker + Time, data = train_data)

# Classification Model (Predicting Tip Category) - KNN 

# Create tip categories (e.g., Low, Medium, High)
train_data_class <- train_data |>
  mutate(TipCategory = case_when(
    Tip < 2 ~ "Low",
    Tip >= 2 & Tip < 4 ~ "Medium",
    Tip >= 4 ~ "High"
  ) |> factor())

test_data_class <- test_data |>
  mutate(TipCategory = case_when(
    Tip < 2 ~ "Low",
    Tip >= 2 & Tip < 4 ~ "Medium",
    Tip >= 4 ~ "High"
  ) |> factor())

tip_class_recipe <- recipe(TipCategory ~ Bill + PartySize + Gender + Smoker + Weekday + Time, data = train_data_class) |>
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) |>
  step_normalize(all_predictors()) # Normalize numerical predictors for KNN

# KNN Model (Fixed k = 5)
knn_model <- nearest_neighbor(neighbors = 5) |>
  set_engine("kknn") |>
  set_mode("classification")

knn_workflow <- workflow() |>
  add_recipe(tip_class_recipe) |>
  add_model(knn_model)

# Fit the model
knn_fit <- knn_workflow |>
  fit(train_data_class)

The linear regression model, predicting TipPercentage, exhibited poor performance, with an RMSE of 4.49, indicating a substantial average prediction error. The low R-squared value of 0.118 suggests that the model explains only a small fraction of the variance in tip percentage. Bill is the most significant predictor, with a negative coefficient (-0.28), suggesting that higher bills are associated with lower tip percentages.

The KNN classification model, predictingÂ TipCategoryÂ with a fixed k of 5, achieved a moderate accuracy of 60.8%. However, the precision, recall, and F1-score, all around 0.53, indicate limitations in accurately classifying specific tip categories. The model performs best for the Medium tip category but has difficulty distinguishing between Low and High.This suggests that while the model correctly predicts the overall category for a decent portion of the data, it struggles to maintain high precision and recall for individual categories.

This indicates that while KNN offers a baseline prediction, its reliability is limited, potentially due to the complexity of tipping behavior and uncaptured influential factors such as service quality or customer satisfaction.

# Feature Selection (Correlation-based)
correlations <- cor(train_data_class |> select_if(is.numeric), as.numeric(train_data_class$TipCategory))
selected_features <- names(correlations[abs(correlations) > 0.2, ]) # Adjust the threshold as needed

# new datasets with selected features
selected_train_data <- train_data_class |> select(all_of(selected_features), TipCategory)
selected_test_data <- test_data_class |> select(all_of(selected_features), TipCategory)

# Retrained KNN with selected features
knn_model_selected <- nearest_neighbor(neighbors = 5) |>
  set_engine("kknn") |>
  set_mode("classification")

knn_workflow_selected <- workflow() |>
  add_recipe(recipe(TipCategory ~ ., data = selected_train_data)) |>
  add_model(knn_model_selected)

knn_fit_selected <- knn_workflow_selected |>
  fit(selected_train_data)

# Predictions with selected features
knn_predictions_selected <- predict(knn_fit_selected, new_data = selected_test_data) |>
  bind_cols(selected_test_data)

# Adjusting prediction column name
if (".pred_class" %in% names(knn_predictions_selected)) {
  knn_predictions_selected <- knn_predictions_selected |>
    rename(.pred = .pred_class)
}

# Metrics with selected features
knn_metrics_selected <- metric_set(accuracy, precision, recall, f_meas)(knn_predictions_selected, truth = TipCategory, estimate = .pred)

print(knn_metrics)

Correlation-based feature selection was employed to enhance the KNN classification modelâs performance in predicting tip categories. By focusing on features with a correlation exceeding an absolute value of 0.2 with the target variable, the retrained model, utilizing only these selected features, exhibited a significant improvement. Specifically, accuracy increased from 60.8% to 86.5%, precision improved from 0.528 to 0.827, recall increased from 0.567 to 0.815, and the F1-score rose from 0.526 to 0.813. These results demonstrate that feature selection effectively reduced noise and emphasized the most informative variables, substantially improving the modelâs ability to accurately classify tip categories, underscoring the importance of feature selection in boosting the performance and reliability of machine learning models.

Exercise 8: Model Comparison

In this exercise, we will compare the performance of the linear regression and Ridge regression models using appropriate metrics to identify the best-performing model.

library(tidymodels)
library(caret) # For feature selection

# Feature Selection for Regression Models (using correlation)
correlations_reg <- cor(train_data |> select_if(is.numeric), train_data$TipPercentage)
selected_features_reg <- names(correlations_reg[abs(correlations_reg) > 0.2, ]) # Adjust threshold as needed

# Create new datasets with selected features
selected_train_data_reg <- train_data |> select(all_of(selected_features_reg), TipPercentage)
selected_test_data_reg <- test_data |> select(all_of(selected_features_reg), TipPercentage)

# Linear Regression Model (with Selected Features)
lm_model <- linear_reg() |>
  set_engine("lm") |>
  set_mode("regression")

lm_fit <- lm_model |>
  fit(TipPercentage ~ ., data = selected_train_data_reg)

lm_predictions <- predict(lm_fit, new_data = selected_test_data_reg) |>
  bind_cols(selected_test_data_reg)

lm_metrics <- metrics(lm_predictions, truth = TipPercentage, estimate = .pred)

# Ridge Regression Model (Fixed penalty = 0.1) (with Selected Features)
ridge_model <- linear_reg(penalty = 0.1, mixture = 0) |>
  set_engine("glmnet") |>
  set_mode("regression")

ridge_recipe <- recipe(TipPercentage ~ ., data = selected_train_data_reg) |>
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors())

ridge_workflow <- workflow() |>
  add_recipe(ridge_recipe) |>
  add_model(ridge_model)

ridge_fit <- fit(ridge_workflow, selected_train_data_reg)

ridge_predictions <- predict(ridge_fit, new_data = selected_test_data_reg) |>
  bind_cols(selected_test_data_reg)

ridge_metrics <- metrics(ridge_predictions, truth = TipPercentage, estimate = .pred)

# Compare Models
